Preprocessing data

Loading the dataset - for the purpose of the exploratory analysis both the original training and test data are used. The total dataset consists of 48842 observations on 15 variables.

# working loc
setwd("/Users/Flora/Documents/Munka/IPEG/test")
vars <- c('age', 'workclass', 'fnlwgt', 'education', 'education_num', 
                    'marital_status', 'occupation', 'relationship', 'race', 'sex', 
                    'capital_gain', 'capital_loss', 'hours_per_week', 'native_country',
                    'label')
data <- read.csv("archive/adult.data", strip.white = T, stringsAsFactors = T, header = F)
colnames(data) <- vars
data_test <- read.csv("archive/adult.test", strip.white = T, stringsAsFactors = T, skip = 1, header = F)
colnames(data_test) <- vars
data <- rbind(data, data_test)

Looks like the dataset contains mostly what is expected. There is some problem with the ‘label’ variable as it has 4 levels, the fnlwgt variable seems to be left unscaled, while there could be some potential outliers in the ‘capital_gain’ and ‘hours_per_week’ variables. Additionally, some of the variables take on ‘?’ as a value, which is used to signal missing/unavailable data.

# fixing 'label'
data[data$label=='<=50K.',]$label <- '<=50K'
data[data$label=='>50K.',]$label <- '>50K'
data$label <- factor(data$label)

# fixed label
summary(data$label)
## <=50K  >50K 
## 37155 11687
# scaling the fnlwgt variable to have mean = 1 and sum = N
data$anwgt <- data$fnlwgt/mean(data$fnlwgt)

In the next few steps, I continue the assessment of the quality of the dataset. First, I have a better look at ‘?’ values, then I check for outliers and duplicate rows, and finally I look for inconsistencies among the variables.

  1. Looking at missing/unknown values
# replace '?' by na for easier handling
data %<>% mutate(across(.fns = ~replace(., . ==  '?' , NA)))

# check for missing data -- NA
data %>% 
    select_if(function(x) any(is.na(x))) %>% 
    summarize(across(.fns = ~sum(is.na(.x)))) -> extra_NA

extra_NA
##   workclass occupation native_country
## 1      2799       2809            857
data_na <- anti_join(data, na.omit(data))
nrow(data_na)
## [1] 3620
nrow(data_na[is.na(data_na$workclass)&is.na(data_na$occupation),])
## [1] 2799

There are a total of 6465 unknown values in the dataset, corresponding for a total of 3620 rows, which means that approximately 7.5% of the observations have missing values. In the case of 2799 observations, both the ‘workclass’ and ‘occupation’ variables are unavailable. Considering the nature of the variables with the missing values, and without any information about previous employment of the individuals, it would be rather difficult to impute the missing data. Similarly, using the available data, it would be difficult to determine the native country of those individuals for whom this information is unknown.

  1. Checking for outliers

To check for outliers, let’s look at the distribution of those variables that potentially contain problematic values, ‘capital_gain’ and ‘hours_per_week’.

  • Capital gain
ggplot(data = data) +
    aes(x=capital_gain, weight = anwgt) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth =5000) + 
    theme_classic()

nrow(data[data$capital_gain > 45000,])
## [1] 244
nrow(data[data$capital_gain==99999,])
## [1] 244
weighted.mean(data$capital_gain, data$anwgt)
## [1] 1063.689
weighted.mean(data[data$capital_gain<99999,]$capital_gain, data[data$capital_gain<99999,]$anwgt)
## [1] 577.7898

It is clear that there are some people with extraordinary high capital gains compared to the rest of the individuals. Moreover, they all have the same value as their capital gain, so it is likely that something is not completely true about these values. However, it is unclear whether they are completely false, or perhaps all larger numbers are just set to the highest possible 5-digit value. Overall, these values are likely to create significant bias: the average capital gain including the observations with extreme capital gaain is approximately USD 1064, while it is only USD 578 if the extreme values are removed.

  • Weekly hours worked
ggplot(data = data) +
    aes(x=hours_per_week, weight = anwgt) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth =3) + 
    theme_classic()

nrow(data[data$hours_per_week > 60,])
## [1] 1676
nrow(data[data$hours_per_week == 99,])
## [1] 137

While the distribution of weekly worked hours also shows some extreme values, it is less likely that these values are false data. In the case of capital gains we could observe a large break between the general larger values of the variable and its maximum, but this is not the case with weekly hours, as several observations fall between the reasonably high number of ours and the maximum of the variable.

  1. Checking duplicates
nrow(data[duplicated(data),])
## [1] 52
#data[duplicated(data),]

The dataset contains 29 duplicated rows. This is a very small proportion of the total amount of available data which can easily be caused by randomness considering how some variables have truly dominant values. Keeping or removing these duplicate rows is not likely to influence the results of data analysis.

Final quality check - visualizations

The easiest way to handle the missing/problematic values is to leave them out of the dataset. To see how this would effect the data overall, let’s look at how the main demographic distributions change if the most problematic rows are removed. As I won’t be using the capital gain and capital loss variables during my further explorations, removing the rows taking on extreme values in this variable is not part of the cleaning process.

# check if demo distribution data w/o rows with missing values and inconsistencies
# is similar to original -- race, age, gender
data_cl <- distinct(data)
data_cl <- data_cl %>% drop_na()
data_cl <- data_cl[!(data_cl$sex == 'Female' & data_cl$relationship == 'Husband'),]
data_cl <- data_cl[!(data_cl$sex == 'Male' & data_cl$relationship == 'Wife'),]
data_cl <- data_cl[!(data_cl$age<20 & data_cl$education_num>12),]
data_cl$workclass <- factor(data_cl$workclass)
data_cl$occupation <- factor(data_cl$occupation)
data_cl$native_country <- factor(data_cl$native_country)
data$total <- 'original'
data_cl$total <- 'cleaned'
plot_data <- rbind(data, data_cl)

AGE

ggplot(plot_data, aes(x=age, fill = total, weight = anwgt)) +
    geom_density(alpha = .4) +
    theme_classic()

GENDER

ggplot(plot_data, aes(x=total, fill=sex, weight = anwgt)) +
    geom_bar(position="fill", stat="count") +
    theme_classic()

RACE

ggplot(plot_data, aes(x=total, fill=race, weight = anwgt)) +
    geom_bar(position="fill", stat="count") +
    theme_classic()

Overall there is little visible difference in the distributions of the ‘cleaned’ and original version of the dataset. The quality of the data is rather good, and the sample size allows for the deletion of 7.5% of the data without causing significant changes in the distribution of the variables according to which the dataset represents the demographic compositions of the US states.

Extracting insights - descriptive statistics

Bivariate explorations

wtd_dt<-svydesign(id=~1, weights=~anwgt, data=data_cl)
svytable(~label, wtd_dt)
## label
##    <=50K     >50K 
## 34062.62 11126.03
round(svymean(~label, wtd_dt),2)
##            mean     SE
## label<=50K 0.75 0.0023
## label>50K  0.25 0.0023

Although the ultimate goal of this exploratory data analysis is not a predictive model, I still chose to explore how the different demographic and labor variables relate to having a higher annual income than $50K. One variable I’m specifically interest in is gender, so I’m trying to explore how someone’s gender influenced the probability of having an income above USD 50K in 1994. Overall, nearly 25% of the sample belongs to the >50K group.

To have an understanding of the variables that are potentially related to having an annual income of above USD 50K, let’s look at how the proportion of individuals having an income above USD 50K is different across the different levels of the demographic and labor variables.

gender x earnings

wtd_dt<-svydesign(id=~1, weights=~anwgt, data=data_cl)
round(svytable(~sex + label, wtd_dt),0)
##         label
## sex      <=50K  >50K
##   Female 12739  1622
##   Male   21324  9504
round(prop.table(svytable(~sex + label, wtd_dt), margin = 1),2)
##         label
## sex      <=50K >50K
##   Female  0.89 0.11
##   Male    0.69 0.31
ggplot(data_cl, aes(x=sex, fill=label, weight = anwgt)) +
    geom_bar(position="fill", stat="count") +
    ylab("share of income categories") +
    theme_classic()

The crosstab shows that the majority of the sample is made of men, which aligns with general assumptions about the US labor force in 1994. As of the proportion of women and men making more than USD 50K, it’s clear that men were in a better position: while barely 11% of women in the sample fall in this category, nearly 31% of men in the sample made more than USD 50K.

age x earnings

ggplot(data = data_cl) +
    aes(x=age, weight = anwgt) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth =3) + 
    theme_classic()

ggplot(data = data_cl) +
    aes(x=age, fill=label, weight = anwgt) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth =3, position='fill') + 
    ylab("share of income categories") +
    theme_classic()

Age and the likelihood of making above USD 50K are also related as expected: until around 50, being older means higher probability to belong in the >50K group, while starting from the age of 50, the probability decreases. Elderly people show a slightly different pattern, however, their absolute number in the sample is marginal.

However, even though their absolute numbers in the sample are very small, individuals in the Asian-Pac-Islander category have the highest probability to make more than USD 50K.

Multivariate plots

In the next section, I visually explore how controlling for some of the variables affects the relationship between gender and the probability of belonging to the >50K group. First, let’s have a look at the relationship of gender, age and high income, and then I investigate the relationship between gender, education and high income.

gender x age x earnings

data_cl$income_high <- ifelse(data_cl$label=='>50K', 1, 0)
# cut age into age groups
data_cl$age_gr <- cut(data_cl$age, breaks = seq(0, 100, 5), right = FALSE)
# gender x education x income
age_data <- aggregate(formula = anwgt ~ sex + age_gr , data = data_cl, FUN = sum)
age_data_h <- aggregate(formula = anwgt ~ sex + age_gr , data = data_cl[data_cl$income_high == 1,], FUN = sum)
age_data_h$population <- ifelse(age_data_h$sex == "Male", -1*age_data_h$anwgt, age_data_h$anwgt)
age_data$population <- ifelse(age_data$sex ==  "Male", -1*age_data$anwgt, age_data$anwgt)

# pyramid chart to display absolute values
ggplot(age_data, aes(x = age_gr, y = population, fill = sex)) + 
    geom_bar(data = subset(age_data, sex == "Female"), stat = "identity", alpha = .5) +
    geom_bar(data = subset(age_data, sex == "Male"), stat = "identity", alpha = .5) + 
    geom_bar(data = subset(age_data_h, sex == "Male"), stat = "identity") + 
    geom_bar(data = subset(age_data_h, sex == "Female"), stat = "identity") + 
    scale_y_continuous(labels = paste0(as.character(c(10000,5000,0,5000)))) + 
    xlab("age") +
    ggtitle("Individuals in the >50K group by gender and age group - absolute values in the sample") +
    coord_flip()

# displaying proportions
age_data_tot <- merge(age_data, age_data_h[,c('age_gr','sex','population')], by=c('age_gr','sex'), all.x = T)
age_data_tot[is.na(age_data_tot$population.y),]$population.y <- 0
age_data_tot$high_prop <- age_data_tot$population.y/age_data_tot$population.x
age_data_rich <- age_data_tot[,c('age_gr', 'sex', 'high_prop')]
colnames(age_data_rich)[3] <- 'population'
age_data_rich$population <- ifelse(age_data_rich$sex == "Male", -1*age_data_rich$population, age_data_rich$population)
age_data_tot$population <- ifelse(age_data_tot$sex == "Male", -1, 1)

# pyramid chart to display proportions
ggplot(age_data_tot, aes(x = age_gr, y = population, fill = sex)) + 
    geom_bar(data = subset(age_data_tot, sex == "Female"), stat = "identity", alpha = .5) +
    geom_bar(data = subset(age_data_tot, sex == "Male"), stat = "identity", alpha = .5) + 
    geom_bar(data = subset(age_data_rich, sex == "Male"), stat = "identity") + 
    geom_bar(data = subset(age_data_rich, sex == "Female"), stat = "identity") + 
    scale_y_continuous(labels = paste0(as.character(c(1,0.5,0,0.5,1)))) + 
    ggtitle("Proportion of individuals in the >50K group by gender and age group") +
    xlab("age")+
    coord_flip()

The pyramid charts displaying the relationship between gender, age and earnigns above <50K suggests that even after controlling for age, the relationship between gender and high income is traceable: except for the oldest people in the sample, out of a woman and man of the same age, the woman is less likely to make more than USD 50K a year.

Once again, the relationship between gender and belonging to the >50K group is not overwritten by the inclusion of education. It is true about all level of education that if a man and a woman have the same level of education, the man will be more likely to make more than USD 50K annually.

Extracting insights - multivariate explorations

So far, we’ve seen that the relationship between gender and the probability of making above USD 50K remains visible even when controlling for some third variables. In the last part of my exploratory analysis, I will make an effort to quantify this relationship, and determine how much more likely are men to belong to the >50K group compared to women. I use logistic regression to investigate this relationship. First, I have a look at some basic models, and I eventually include most available control variables.

  1. Basic univariate model (odds ratio could be also read from contingency table)
model1 <- glm(income_high ~ sex, data = data_cl, family = binomial, weights = anwgt)

Our first univariate model suggests that for men the odds of making more than 50K a year is 3.5 times as much as for women. As expected with the large sample size, this value is statistically significant, with a 95% confidence interval of 3.3 and 3.7.

Finally, the last model including most variables available in the dataset as controls (using three age groups instead of continous age, the numerical version of education, transformed version of relationship, binary version of native country and ignoring the capital gain and loss variables), we can see that the relationship between gender and belonging to the higher income group weakens: eventually, if we compare a man and a woman coming from the same demographic background and working in a similar position, the odds ratio of belonging to the >50K group decreases to 1.2.

To get a sense of the quality of the logistic regression model, I run a Hosmer-Lemeshow goodness of fit test.

hltest(data_cl$income_high, model3$fitted.values)

Unfortunately, the test provides evidence for the poor fit of the model. To find a better model and investigate more how gender and membership in the >50K group are related, it would be beneficial to further transform variables/include extra information not available in the dataset.

Conclusion

In this data analysis I focused two things:

First, I assessed the quality of the data at hand. As the description of the datafile mentioned, the dataset came reasonably cleaned. Some of the remaining issues to be handled were missing/unknown values, duplicates, outliers, and inconsistencies within the variables. With the variables at hand, some of the problematic values would be rather difficult to impute/correct, while in the case of other values, successful imputation seems more likely. For the puprose of the current analysis, I decided to either not use the problematic variables or simply leave out the observations containing the problematic values. I visually demonstrated how this tranformation does not change the representativeness of the data along the variables (gender, race, age) that were used in the weighting process.

Second, I focused on extracting insights from the dataset. My goal was to investigate how gender and belonging to the group that makes more than USD 50K yearly are related. First, I prepared charts to visually investigate the relationship between the available demographic/labor variables and the outcome variable of belonging to the >50K group. Afterwards, I created further visualizations to demonstrate whether the relationship between gender and >50K gorup membership remains after controlling for some demographic variables. Finally, I ran logistic regression models to quantify the relationship. The bivariate OR of 3.5 (e.g. men having 3.5 the odds compared to women to belong to the >50K group) decreased to an OR of 1.3 after including most control variables.
